* The following insight from user "natsb88" (note: I have not verified this at all, so take it as his opinion/speculation only):  
Resistivity increases from left to right as you are looking at your PMV screen. A reading out to the right means higher resistivity than expected.  
 nbsp;  
Pure silver is very conductive (and therefore has a low resistivity). In fact, silver is the single most conductive metal. Which means as soon as you start to add atoms of anything else to silver, even in trace amounts, they begin to interfere with the flow of electrons through the metal. How much they interfere (meaning how much they decrease conductivity / increase resistivity) depends not only on the amount of foreign atoms, but also what they are. Some metals will cause a greater loss in conductivity than others, even when present at the same percentage by mass. (This is why 90% coin silver is so challenging to categorize...that other 10% is nominally copper, which is about 95% as conductive as silver, but as soon as you drop in a trace of something like lead, which is only 7% as conductive as silver, it throws everything off).  
 nbsp;  
Temperature also affects electrical conductivity, and therefore the PMV reading. Metals become more conductive at lower temperatures, thus exhibiting lower resistivity, and less conductive at higher temperatures, thus exhibiting higher resistivity. (If you find this phenomenon interesting, go to YouTube and look up superconductors.) So cold temps will move the block left and hot temps will move the block right. For accurate testing, the Verifier and metal should both be at room temperature.

* Also of note to the above, "natsb88" sent off the worst "offender" from his tubes (read 3 blocks to the right) and shipped it out to testing. I didn't include it in my previous points, but others have also sent coins off to ST and/or for independent assaying using pre and post melt XRF and other verification.  

* I'm going to quote the definitive answer from "nats88" from the assay results he got back, as well as his conclusions (page 10 and 11 of the thread):   

They first tested the round as-is on both surfaces.
 nbsp;  
Average Before Melting
.9988 Ag
.0012 Pt  
 nbsp; 
They then melted the round into a homogeneous blob and tested it again.  
 nbsp;  
Average After Melting
.9999 Ag  
 nbsp;  
Now, if there really was a trace amount of platinum in the alloy, it would still be there after melting. Since the metal assays at .9999 after melting, it really is pure silver. So what is going on here?  
 nbsp;  
These results suggest a very minor surface contaminant on the rounds. Something that interferes with surface testing, but burns away when you melt the silver.  
 nbsp;  
If you do an XRF assay through a plastic slab, it will often show a trace amount of Pt and/or Pd in the results. That is not actually in the coin, but is the result of interference from the plastic. This would suggest that other non-metallic substances could throw off the results too.  
 nbsp;  
A round going through the minting process could be exposed to lubricants from any of the hundreds of moving parts in the production line. There could be a small amount of oil or some other release agent on the dies. The blanks could be washed with a cleaning solution prior to coining that doesn't fully rinse away. Anything on the surface of the blank or the dies at the time of coining will essentially be embedded into the first couple thousandths of an inch of material, meaning it won't simply wash away later.  
 nbsp;  
A minor surface contaminant could interfere with the PMV's electrical testing similarly to how it can interfere with an XRF assay. The variance from one round to another within the same tube (some rounds reading as expected, some rounds reading 2-3 blocks to the right) also supports the idea of a surface contaminant increasing the resistivity of the round. It is very unlikely for the metal content to vary from one round to another within the same production batch, but completely plausible that some type of minor surface contaminant would vary from one round to the next.
 nbsp;  
Once I get the melted round back, which assayed at .9999 fine, I will test it with the PMV again to make sure it reads as expected. I will also continue to pursue some hardness testing to see if variance in annealing and coining could contribute to the different readings.  
 nbsp;  
The takeaway from all of this should be:  
 nbsp;  
- The 2015 Silvertowne Buffalo rounds really are .999+ silver :thumbup:  
 nbsp;  
- The PMV is a very sensitive and useful tool, but you need to know what it measures, how it does it, and what can affect the results. It is not meant to replace the human brain, so don't turn yours off when you use it :thumbup:  
 nbsp;  
- Keep calm and stack on :thumbup:    

 nbsp;  second post

After discussing this more with Sigma they do not believe the slightly right PMV readings to be due to a non-metal surface contaminant, but perhaps due to micro cracks in the surface of the rounds from the minting process. Such cracks would be plausible if Silvertowne is not annealing or fully annealing the blanks before coining, or are coining at particularly high pressures. Those cracks would affect the PMV reading but would obviously disappear when the round is melted. In that case I'm not sure what would be causing the slightly 999 initial XRF assay though. I actually wouldn't be surprised if Silvertowne figured out a way to skip the annealing process on these. They are cranking out an ungodly number of these rounds at miniscule margins for their eBay promotions. The design is also very shallow and not so crisp. Could be that they skip the traditional annealing step and just crank up the coining pressure on these. Just postulating here...  
 nbsp;  
In any case, whatever is causing the unusual surface readings on these rounds does indeed disappear when melted. Below is a photo of the silver round that was melted and assayed a second time for the "after" results. I rolled it flat enough to test with the small wand and it now reads inside the brackets. It read 3 blocks to the right of the brackets before melting.

 Good news for us silver snobs, 999 4 life!   
